Wolf Performance 45acp steel cased FMJ seven 50rd boxes $150 for a total of 350 rounds.

I completely understand that these prices are more than what you paid 6 months ago. I bought these 9mm rounds 3 years ago for about 20 cents per round--which was also significantly less than what the ammo was selling for 6 months ago--and stored them in 50cal ammo cans. I am perfectly content to leave my ammo in my ammo cans. I am of the opinion that 4-6 months from now, the price of ammunition will settle down again, but will settle at a somewhat higher "normal" price. A lot of people have a gloomier outlook on the subject. 

However, I went to Bill Goodman's on Sunday. There was ZERO 9mm target ammunition to be had AT ANY PRICE. No one locally and no one online has any in stock, except cheaperthandirt... if you are willing to pay $21.19 per 50 for steel cased ammo, plus shipping. 

If you are filling ammo cans for doomsday, wait until summer, I think prices will come back down some, and probably settle around $14-15/50 for brass target 9mm. Or, keep running up to Walmart at 7am each day to check for anything in stock...they have a 3 50rd box limit, and the 9mm is just under $15/50. If you want good range ammo for this weekend, email me. I'm letting 1000 rounds go, and I am keeping the rest.

title: For Sale:  Fight for your rights
postcontent:
The DFL is coming after us and we need to fight back. Please copy the letter below and email it to all state Representatives.

Stop the Insanity!
This nation witnessed a tragic event on December 14th 2012 when a disturbed young man murdered twenty children and seven adults, but that is not the Insanity I am referring to. The true insanity came immediately after the shooting when gun control supporters climbed over the dead bodies of the children and used them to once again try and dismantle the Constitution of the United States. What is the goal of those once again calling for gun control? Is their goal to make a safer society or are they just pushing their personal agendas. The Justice Department concluded that the previous gun ban of 1994 had no effect in reducing gun crime, should we not learn from previous mistakes and seek a new and better path to deal with violent criminals and those who are truly disturbed and violent. Criminals do not obey laws; this is why we call them criminals. No gun control law will keep guns out of the hands of criminals and anyone determined to commit a heinous crime such as the Newtown shooting will find a way. I am not scared of being involved in a mass shooting; there is greater chance that I will be killed by a tornado. What does scare me is the Governor of New York passing a law in the dark of night when no one was watching. What does scare me is the way in which our elected officials are demonizing inanimate objects and trying to subvert the Constitution rather than look for a real solution to these phenomena. What does scare me is the total lack of logic being used by our elected officials. Banning fire arms based on how they look or how many bullets they hold is illogical and does not address the real causes of the crimes. These heinous acts are not the norm and law abiding citizens should not be punished due the action of a few disturbed individuals. As a resident of Minnesota I am offended that you would seek to punish the innocent rather than seek a real answer to these phenomena. According to the FBI there were a total of 70 homicides in Minnesota in 2011. 43 of these homicides involved firearms and only 3 of those involved rifles of all types, equal to the number killed with hands and feet. 16 times more people were killed with knives or other weapons. Demonizing guns is not the answer, making law abiding citizens criminals is not the answer. We have witnessed a continuous drop in violent crime over the last 20 years, so what is the agenda of the gun control proponents? None of the legislation being proposed will affect the crime rates in a positive manner nor will they stop the heinous acts committed by the mentally disturbed. Our nation was deeply divided before the Newtown shooting and the irresponsible acts of gun control proponents are only dividing the nation further. I urge you to abandon this reckless legislation (H.F. 241) and address the real issues facing us as a state and the nation as a whole.

title: For Sale/Trade:  rare 1930 Polish training rifle
postcontent: Pre WWII polish military training rifle in excellent mechanical and cosmetic condition. Very scarce Polish pre-World War Two wz. 1930 A single shot sporting rifle! The rifle displays following markings on the barrel: "P.W.U. Fabryka Karabinow Warszawa" (on the left side), and "K.B.K.S. Wz.A Patent No.72A Kal. 22 long rifle" (on the right side). The left side of the receiver ring displays a serial number. "Kbk.S" is a Polish language abbreviation that stands for, "karabinek sportowy" (sporting carbine). Accordingly, "wz" (wzor) will translate to "model", or "pattern". Matching serial numbers (the matching serial numbers are stamped on the receiver and bolt only; other parts of the rifle do not have serial numbers, which is correct for this model). The serial numbers are factory original, and they were not restamped. The rifle has an original blue finish on metal. Sporting style front sight with protective hood. Sporting style, adjustable rear sights calibrated from 25 to 100 meters. The rifle was manufactured without a finger groove in the forestock. Hardened rubber buttplate with diamond checkering and letters, "FK" (Fabryka Karabinow w Warszawie). Steel trigger guard. Two sporting style sling swivels. Correct bolt with straight handle. The bolt, the rear sights, the safety mechanism, as well as the rifle itself were patented in Poland. This Rifle is in excellent mechanical as well  as cosmetic shape. These rifles are worth 1,200-2,400$ as seen here http://www.collectiblefirearms.com/Rifles22.html but as this one has a 1.3 inch long fracture in the grip which was pinned for repair in Poland, I am only asking 500 for this rare and historically relevant firearm
